snippet.title: HOW TO TRAVEL ROME ON A BUDGET -- Budget Travel Tips  //  141
snippet.description:
I spent 5 days in Rome and only spend $159.84. I even splurged a bit. 

Transportation 0:58 
Food 5:44
Accommodation 9:03
Attractions 9:33

Here's the breakdown of how I traveled Rome on a budget:
ACCOMMODATION: 
Hostel bed: $51.25
City Tax: $18.00
Total: $69.25

FOOD:
Ravioli dinner with Tiramisu: $17.17 
Fancy antipasta with Cappucino: $22.13
Gelato: $3.09
Groceries (yogurt, apples, pasta, sauce, wine): $9.90
Total: $52.29

ATTRACTIONS:
Walking Tour: $15.38
Total: $15.38

TRANSPORTATION:
Bus: $7.43
Bus: $7.43
Metro: $8.06
Total: $22.92

ALL TOGETHER: $159.84.

For five days in Rome, I spent under $160. This is fantastic, considering Rome is an expensive city in an expensive country! But if you're wondering how to travel Rome on a budget, or looking for some budget travel tips, you've come to the right place. 

The best tips are included in the video, but for those who just want to read and continue on preparing for your trip, remember these key points:
1. If you want to keep to your Rome trip budget, walk as much as possible.
2. If you want to eat on a budget in Rome, buy groceries and cook (some) meals.
3. If you need cheap accommodation in Rome, stay in a hostel or AirBnB.
4. If you're looking for free things to do in Rome, visit the many free attractions (the Vatican, Giancolo Hill, The Colosseum (outside), the parks, Trastevere, the river, etc.)

This last one is a big one. It is easy to throw money at private tours or special tours. Some of those tours might be amazing. But you're at a point in your life where you can't afford the pricey amazing, just the budget amazing. Thankfully, there are a lot of free things to do in Rome, so the budget amazing is actually worth your time.

MORE QUESTIONS?! I'm happy to hear that. Leave them in the comments and I'll get back to you ASAP. ;)

We were in Rome less than a year ago and did almost the same thing as you. We did buy the Roman pass and used Airbnb and was much better than a hotel. We were happy to not have to pay to see all the things and didn’t have any FOMO (fear of missing out). I loved walking the cobblestone streets, drinking water out of the free fountains and absorbing the Roman culture. Before our trip I purchased a few travel books and the one from Rick Steves is the BEST ever and highly recommend!
Thanks for your video, Jacey!

comments.textDisplay: This video reminds me of Malta where I am living in right now, very near from Sicily. Those where fireworks my dear. There must have been a Festa in that town, same as in Malta,,oh let’s talk about beautiful Rome. I have been to Rome 23 times. Will be back this January.. Yes the cheapest way from the airport to the center of Rome is definitely by bus, a return trip will cost only €9 . Always eat at a local Italian restaurant, good tasty food at a reasonable price. Also fill up a water bottle from any one of Rome’s many water fountains, it’s safe to drink and it’s free..Also walking around is also free. I use Agoda.com to book my Hotel, and I normally pay €50 per night for a 4 star Hotel,single room with bathroom, free WiFi and breakfast. Breakfast is great because you can make a huge sandwich, yogurt,fruit and take them out with you, basically a free lunch. So for €50 per night gets you a private room, with breakfast and free lunch, not to mention privacy..Thanks for you lovely video..
